cs.CG, cs.DM, cs.DS, cs.GT, cs.SI. 

The paper deals with a problem in computational geometry, specifically the packing of plane spanning trees into a point set. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves combinatorial arguments and graph theory, which suggests that it could also belong to cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The use of lower bounds and geometric graphs could place it in cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) as well. Finally, the paper involves some analysis of the dimension of a set of points, which could make it relevant to cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
